r, <strong>The Boy Next Door</strong>. While the musical side of her career is undoubtedly flourishing, the movie side – to put it mildly – is suffering from malign neglect.</p> <p>Exhibit A: The Boy Next Door, shot in 23 days for next to nothing – and boy, does it show. “We put all $4m in front of the camera!” exulted the star recently, inadvertently highlighting the movie’s myriad shortcomings behind it. For instance, a screenwriter who thinks there’s such a thing as “a first edition of the Iliad”, not to mention the director or the 100 people on set who might have spotted that howler before it went globally viral a month ago, having evidently drawn no comment during postproduction, either. I will admit some grudging admiration, however, for any movie featuring the line: “Dude, you gotta read the Iliad!”</p>  <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MgbBwovOOoc\"                                                                                                > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/MgbBwovOOoc?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> </figure>  <p>The speaker of that line, the eponymous neighbour-hunk Noah (Ryan Guzman), falls hard for trial-separated mother J-Lo. She’s also his teacher, which is interesting because, although the screenplay never bothers to tell us why, he’s 20 years old and still in high school. They end up in bed after a ton of early-warning justifications in the script for a teacher sleeping with her hunky student: she’s feeling vulnerable; she had a bad date earlier; her philandering husband (John Corbett) is bugging her; she’s had a couple of drinks; and <em>God damn</em>, would you just look at those abs! Plus he tells her: “A woman like you should be cherished, Claire...”</p> <p>Big mistake. She tries to end it. The kid doesn’t like rejection (“I love your mom’s cookies!” he tells her son at one particularly toothsome moment). It turns out he has a violent streak and a dodgy past back in San Bernardino – a city that Hollywood routinely slanders as an inland white-trash hellhole – and thenceforth he’s stalking and harassing J-Lo, eyeing the brakes on Corbett’s midlife crisis-mobile (portending a thrill-free runaway car sequence later), pouring poison in her son’s ear then boinking his prom date, and so on. Each escalation is less plausible than the last, and the climactic fight is a letdown.</p> <p>All the signs were there: a powerful star, a malleable director, a newcomer-hunk, a dim-wattage male co-star (Corbett is so ultra-safe it’s like he’s been spayed). It’s all very insecure, late-50s Joan Crawford stuff. And everything in it can be found in a far better realised, albeit no less trashy thriller that J-Lo made in 2002 with Michael Apted, in which she flees cross-country from a monstrously violent husband, played to the absolute nines by Billy Campbell.</p> <p>That movie was called Enough. The Boy Next Door is its exact opposite: Not Nearly Enough.</p>","headline":"The Boy Next Door: J-Lo stars in the mother of all misfires","trailText":"Between the ads and the albums, Jennifer Lopez has found time to star in this trashy thriller. She needn’t have bothered<br>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/2/18/1424278859096/b64422a6-af4a-447c-8d38-0bb424dda114-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"480","commentable":"false","byline":"John Patterson","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2015-02-28T09:00:00+00:00"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/feb/23/the-boy-next-door-jennifer-lopez","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/2015/feb/23/the-boy-next-door-jennifer-lopez","sectionName":"Film","tags":[{"id":"film/film","webTitle":"Film","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/film","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/film","sectionName":"Film","refer