ationship with his doting mother.</p> <p>This exuberantly demonstrative melodrama is the latest film from another enfant terrible, 25-year-old director <a href=\"http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0230859/\">Xavier Dolan</a>. <em>Mommy</em> caused <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/may/21/cannes-2014-review-mommy\">much excitement in Cannes last year</a> – where it shared the Jury Prize with Jean-Luc Godard - and it certainly got Pilon noticed, one review hailing him as a cross between Jean-Paul Belmondo and “<a href=\"http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/mommy-cannes-review-706363\">a demonically cherubic Macaulay Culkin</a>”.</p> <p>Despite the excitement, <em>Mommy</em> is not the most controversial thing that Pilon and Dolan have done together; that was a video for <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Rp5U5mdARgY\">College Boy</a> by French group Indochine. The song is insipid, the video anything but: carrying an anti-bullying message, it stars Pilon as a brutalised schoolboy martyr. “My character gets crucified, shot, pissed on,” he says, slipping from French into English. “It was pretty intense. Xavier wanted people to feel directly attacked, to face them with something they didn’t want to feel implicated in.”</p> <p>Olivier and his older sister got the acting bug young, watching children on TV and wondering how they’d got there. When he was 10, he asked his parents to enter him for auditions, and he got his first lead film role two years later. He has been a fixture in Canadian film and TV ever since, but <em>Mommy</em> – which recently won him best actor in the Canadian Screen Awards – has really made people recognise him. That has its drawbacks. “People get scared to see me in the street, because they think I’m like the character in the movie.” It can only get worse, given his ambition: “I just want to work on even more intense characters now.”</p> <p>It’s quite a relief to be able to follow Pilon’s French: in person, his Québécois accent has only a mild twang as opposed to the teeth-aching intensity of the version in <em>Mommy</em>. The film exaggerates for effect, Pilon explains: “I normally wouldn’t speak like Steve every day.” Born in Montreal, Pilon spent six years of his childhood on the eastern peninsula of <a href=\"https://www.google.co.uk/maps/place/Peninsule+de+la+Gaspesie,+Mont-Albert,+QC+G0E,+Canada/@48.6184758,-66.3057454,5z/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x4c99f0d712a2398d:0x75252761901b49dd\">Gaspésie</a>. “The accent there is quite close to Steve’s,” Pilon says, giving me a sing-song sample, really putting his gullet into it. In France, he adds, “They can’t make head or tail of it – they have to show <em>Mommy</em> there with subtitles.”</p>","headline":"Antoine Olivier Pilon: ‘I just want to work on even more intense characters now’","trailText":"Antoine Olivier Pilon plays a troubled teen in Mommy – next, he wants to go badder","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/3/6/1425664423626/1058a7c8-59d7-4b68-8418-4f8d946f8353-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"458","commentable":"true","byline":"Jonathan Romney","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2015-04-05T23:45:00+01:00"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/mar/15/mommy-antoine-olivier-pilon-interview-even-more-intense-characters","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/2015/mar/15/mommy-antoine-olivier-pilon-interview-even-more-intense-characters","sectionName":"Film","tags":[{"id":"film/mommy","webTitle":"Mommy","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/mommy","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/mommy","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"film/film","webTitle":"Film","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/film","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/film","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture"