wn by the arrival of refugees from Paris and jackbooted soldiers from Berlin. Horrified at being billeted an officer from the invading army, haughty Madame Angellier (a fearsomely taut Kristin Scott Thomas) and her winsomely hectored daughter-in-law Lucile (Michelle Williams) become the subject of a vicious whispering campaign by the villagers from whom they have extorted high rents for years. In stark contrast to such native hostility, handsome German officer Bruno von Falk (Matthias Schoenaerts) proves a disturbingly charming house guest, playing poignant melodies on Madame Angellier’s lock-and-keyed piano, and discreetly wooing the flustered Lucile about whose soldier-husband little is heard but rumour. Meanwhile, hot-headed Benoît (Sam Riley) treats his landlords as contemptible collaborators as he struggles to keep the Nazis’ hands off his wife and family, a wounded leg doing little to dampen his fiery pro-resistance zeal.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/video/2015/mar/12/suite-francaise-video-review\"                data-short-url=\"http://gu.com/p/46hqa\"                        data-show-ads=\"true\"                data-video-id=\"2256967\"                data-video-name=\"Suite Française - video review\"                data-video-provider=\"guardian.co.uk\"                data-video-poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2015/3/12/1426172000407/crop_KP_119166_640x360.jpeg\"> <video data-media-id=\"gu-video-455870476\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2015/3/12/1426171995953/crop_KP_119166_1200x720.jpeg\"> <source src=\"http://multimedia.guardianapis.com/interactivevideos/video.php?octopusid=10140172&amp;format=video/mp4\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/webM/2015/03/12/150312SuiteFrancaiseReview_synd_768k_vp8.webm\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2015/03/12/150312SuiteFrancaiseReview_large.3gp\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/HLS/2015/03/12/150312SuiteFrancaiseReview.m3u8\"></source><source src=\"http://multimedia.guardianapis.com/interactivevideos/video.php?octopusid=10140172&amp;format=video/3gp&amp;maxwidth=700\"></source> </video> </figure>  <p>The now-celebrated origins of <em>Suite Française</em>, which became a publishing sensation in 2004, are as startling and extraordinary as anything on screen – arguably more so. Having fled Paris as the Nazis approached in 1940, the Ukrainian-Jewish writer <a href=\"http://jwa.org/encyclopedia/article/nemirovsky-irene\">Irène Némirovsky</a> relocated to Issy-l’Evêque in Burgundy, where she began work on a planned five-part tale of war and peace. But after being transported to Auschwitz, Némirovsky died (aged just 39) in 1942, her notebooks entrusted to her daughters Denise and Elisabeth, who believed them to be diaries. It wasn’t until the 1990s that Denise discovered what turned out to be the first two instalments of Némirovsky’s extraordinary unfinished work. Published under the umbrella title <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/mar/04/featuresreviews.guardianreview2\"><em>Suite Française</em></a>, these two self-contained novellas were reportedly optioned by Hollywood’s Universal Pictures. But by 2007 the title had returned to the French ownership of TF1, with whom British co-writer/director Saul Dibb has brought this French/UK/Belgian co-production to the screen.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4cR0L6invGQ\"                                                                                                > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/4cR0L6invGQ?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> </figure>  <p>Inventively distilling the essence of its source stories, Dibb and co-writer Matt Charman (whose credits include Spielberg’s forthcoming cold war thriller <em>Bridge of Spies</em>) interpose the Parisian exodus of the first novella, <em>Storm in June, </em>into the rural melodrama of the second, <em>Dolce,</em> to create a satisfyingly rounded yet neatly compact narrative. While the core romantic conceit may be familiar (the “sleeping with the enemy” scenario is a well-worn war-drama staple) the blurred lines and conflicted loyalties with which Dibb and Charman grapple are rewardingly complex and disarmingly compassionate.</p> <p>Although several characters seem at first glance to be trading in generic archetypes, the movie takes pleasure in wrong-footing our expectations, nowhere more so than in the character of Madame Angellier, whose icy surface hides oceans of anxiety and grief (I was reminded of Miranda Richardson’s Miss Lorimer in James Kent’s flawed but heartfelt recent adaptation of<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jan/18/testament-of-youth-review-tame-adaptation-vera-brittain-book\"> <em>Testament of Youth</em></a>). Indeed, one of the film’s most striking sequences features a moment of life-and-death tenderness between two characters who have previously been tarred as all but irredeemable, supporting players Harriet Walter and Lambert Wilson stealing the movie out from under its stars’ noses with pitch-perfect precision and understatement.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--supporting\" data-media-id=\"2ce63c680ab0b9dcc5768763756977f2d7804e99\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/3/11/1426089608893/5b090ae4-ba56-44ba-820b-c13507373448-280x420.jpeg\" alt=\"Kristin Scott Thomas as Madame Angellier.\" width=\"280\" height=\"420\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Kristin Scott Thomas as Madame Angellier.</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Amid the sociopolitical intrigues of occupied village life with which the labyrinthine narrative is primarily concerned, the putative love story between Lucile and Bruno can prove the least interesting element. Both Williams and Schoenaerts are talented players, but there’s a peculiar absence to Lucile’s character (unaided by her dreary voiceover) that is at odds with Williams’s sparklingly complex and engaging work in films like <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/jan/16/blue-valentine-review-michelle-williams-ryan-gosling\"><em>Blue Valentine</em></a><em> </em>and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/apr/17/meeks-cutoff-review\"><em>Meek’s Cutoff</em></a>. Yet even this may be a strength rather than a weakness, reminding us that the problems of these two little people really <em>don’t</em> amount to a hill of beans in this crazy world, pointing us instead towards the tortured heroism of Benoît, the downtrodden defiance of Ruth Wilson’s Madeleine, and the stoical resilience of those who refuse to live “on German time”.</p> <p>Handsomely shot on 35mm by cinematographer Eduard Grau, <em>Suite Française</em> benefits from well-chosen Belgian locations (Marville provides a splendid setting for Bussy’s bustling town square) which add depth, texture, and a tangible sense of history. Production designer Michael Carlin, who was Oscar-nominated for his work on Dibb’s previous feature <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2008/sep/07/periodandhistorical\"><em>The Duchess</em></a>, continues to prove his worth, creating a world that extends beyond the edge of the frame, a canvas as broad and detailed as the characters themselves. Sensible, too, to have the English-language “French” dialogue delivered without the cod-European accents beloved of Hollywood, Dibb opting instead to utilise the distinctive class inflections of his mother tongue to tease out themes of historical injustice and inequality that existed long before the (German-speaking) Nazis arrive.</p> <p>In its weaker moments, <em>Suite Française </em>tends somewhat toward soft-soapiness, the tinkling piano theme with which Bruno proves his inner spirituality (penned by Alexandre Desplat) merging into Rael Jones’s love-and-war score in ripely sentimental fashion. Yet there are more than enough rough edges in this portrait of a town torn apart to override any melodramatic gloss, and an impressive sense of balance that belies the tumultuous birth of Némirovsky’s handwritten manuscripts, which heartbreakingly accompany the closing credits.</p>","headline":"Suite Française review – rewardingly complex and disarmingly compassionate","trailText":"This handsome adaptation of Irène Némirovsky’s epic novel vividly depicts French rural life under the Nazis","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/3/11/1426089083713/SUITE-FRANCAISE-001.jpg","wordcount":"841","commentable":"true","starRating":"3","byline":"Mark Kermode, Observer film critic","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2015-04-05T15:46:00+01:00"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/mar/15/suite-francaise-review-kermode-complex-compassionate","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/2015/mar/15/suite-francaise-review-kermode-complex-compassionate","sectionName":"Film","tags":[{"id":"film/suite-francaise","webTitle":"Suite Française","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/suite-francaise","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/suite-francaise","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"film/series/mark-kermode-film-of-the-week","webTitle":"Mark Kermode's film of the week","description":"Films of the week reviewed by the Observer's film critic Mark Kermode","type":"series","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/series/mark-kermode-film-of-the-week","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/film/series/mark-kermode-film-of-the-week","sectionName":"Film","references":[]},{"id":"film/film","webTitle":"Film","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","webUrl":"http:/