m/film/nicolas-roeg\">Nicolas Roeg</a>), which premiered at the last year’s London film festival.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/mar/12/terence-stamp-i-was-in-my-prime-but-when-the-60s-ended-i-ended-with-it\">Terence Stamp: ‘I was in my prime, but when the 60s ended, I ended with it’</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Adapted with reverence and wit by screenwriter Frederic Raphael, the film is splendidly lusty fare, its feet deep in the mud of the English countryside, its head in the lens-flared glare of a dreamy tragi-romantic sky. Even through the soft-focus close-ups, Julie Christie (whose casting was considered controversial) cuts a striking figure as Bathsheba Everdene, variously wooed by Alan Bates’s earthy Gabriel Oak, Peter Finch’s landed William Boldwood and Terence Stamp’s dashingly caddish Sergeant Francis “Frank” Troy. The scene in which a roaring Frank demonstrates his swordsmanship to a gasping Bathsheba remains a masterclass in subversive erotic suggestion – faintly ridiculous, yes, but still quite dazzling.</p> <p>Richard Rodney Bennett earned an Oscar nomination for his score, but it’s Roeg’s photography that seduces and ravishes the viewer; a reverse zoom from a flock of sheep gives us a God’s-eye view of the landscape in a manner that still takes the breath away after nearly 50 years. Vinterberg may be a fine director, but he is going to have a very hard task topping this.</p>","headline":"Far From the Madding Crowd review – still quite dazzling","trailText":"John Schlesinger’s 1967 film of Hardy’s novel, ravishingly shot by Nicholas Roeg, is hard to beat","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Columnist/Columnists/2015/3/13/1426264385786/far-from-the-madding-crow-001.jpg","wordcount":"231","commentable":"true","starRating":"4","byline":"Mark Kermode Observer film critic","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentClose