ta-canonical-url=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/video/2015/mar/12/x-plus-y-video-review\"                data-short-url=\"http://gu.com/p/46tvk\"                        data-show-ads=\"true\"                data-video-id=\"2257004\"                data-video-name=\"X+Y - video review\"                data-video-provider=\"guardian.co.uk\"                data-video-poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2015/3/12/1426173446976/crop_640x360.jpeg\"> <video data-media-id=\"gu-video-455871183\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2015/3/12/1426173442282/crop_1200x720.jpeg\"> <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2015/03/12/150312xplusy4_desk.mp4\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2015/03/12/150312xplusy4_small.3gp\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/HLS/2015/03/12/150312xplusy4.m3u8\"></source><source src=\"http://multimedia.guardianapis.com/interactivevideos/video.php?octopusid=10140174&amp;format=video/3gp&amp;minwidth=700\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/webM/2015/03/12/150312xplusy4_synd_768k_vp8.webm\"></source> </video> </figure>  <p>As Nathan, Butterfield, who impressed in <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/hugo\"><em>Hugo</em></a> and the underrated <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/ender-s-game\"><em>Ender’s Game</em></a><em>,</em> is ably guided by director Morgan Matthews, who draws on his Bafta-nominated documentary <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2007/oct/21/features.review27\"><em>Beautiful Young Minds</em></a> for insight into Nathan’s place on the spectrum of neurodevelopmental disorders. The result is rather charming, often funny, occasionally surprising and consistently heartwarming.</p>","headline":"X+y review – heartwarming and funny story of maths prodigy","trailText":"Lovely performances from Rafe Spall, Sally Hawkins and Asa Butterfield d