C and why Oprah Winfrey is responsible for the turnaround in her life<br /><br /><a href=\" http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/dec/13/lindsay-lohan-interview-london-stage-debut\" title=\"\">• Lindsay Lohan interview: ‘I needed to grow up’</a>","hasStoryPackage":"true","body":"<p><strong> </strong></p> <p>A rehabilitated Lindsay Lohan says she will not return to the paparazzi flashes of Los Angeles and is instead planning to make London her permanent home.</p> <p>In an interview with the <em>Observer</em>, the actor, 28, who has had a troubled past with alcohol and drugs, enthused about her love affair with London life and the anonymity it has to offer. Not to mention her soft spot for the BBC. “I love the BBC,” said Lohan. “I haven’t heard myself mentioned on TV since I have been here. That has been really weird for me, and great.”</p> <p>Lohan, who has lived in the capital for nine months, has a lease for another year on her flat in the West End and is currently planning to make it her permanent residence. “I won’t live in LA again, hell no. My friends tell me shit when they come over I don’t want to hear,” said Lohan. “I don’t even know who got married and who got pregnant. You turn on the news in LA and it is all gossip about people. All the stuff that is going on in the world right now and this gossip is the news? I can go for a run here [London] on my own ... I do every morning, early, and I think how my friends in New York would still be up partying at that time. I needed to grow up and London is a better place for me to do that than anywhere else. In LA I didn’t know what to do, apart from go out every night. That’s when my friends were free. And I would go out and there would be all these cameras there and that’s when it became difficult.”</p> <p>Lohan, who recently starred in the West End play <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/oct/05/speed-the-plow-lindsay-lohan-review-playhouse-london-schiff-lindsay-posner\" title=\"\"><em>Speed-the-Plow</em></a>, decided to turn her back on the west coast while holidaying alone in Greece over the summer. It was the first time she had ever been on holiday by herself. “I just wandered about on my own! I turned my phone off. It was so extraordinarily freeing for me. Like another life.”</p> <p>She credits the turnaround in her life, in part, to Oprah Winfrey. Winfrey provided Lohan with the self-help book <a href=\"http://bookshop.theguardian.com/untethered-soul.html\" title=\"\"><em>The Untethered Soul</em></a> by Michael Singer, and it has since become Lohan’s “bible”, guiding her away from the destructive voice in her head. “There’s a chapter called ‘The Rose and the Thorn’, you sit on a couch and you imagine that voice in your head as a person next to you. You learn how to distance yourself from that person.”</p> <p>The second stage of her transformation, according to the interview, was learning to be punctual – now she is determined not to miss any appointments, especially when it comes to her stage work in London.</p> <p>“One time I was sick with a bug. I had been vomiting all day, but no way was I going to miss a show. I was sitting there beforehand seeing spots in front of my eyes. I had a plan: if I felt sick on stage I was going to faint, play dead, pretend it was part of the script. Didn’t happen, fortunately.”</p>","headline":"Lindsay Lohan: why I want to make London my home","trailText":"Actor talks about her love affair with the capital, the BBC and why Oprah Winfrey is responsible for the turnaround in her life<br /><br /><a href=\" http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/dec/13/lindsay-lohan-interview-london-stage-debut\" title=\"\">• Lindsay Lohan interview: ‘I needed to grow up’</a>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/12/14/1418549321890/Lindsay-Lohan-in-Speed-th-006.jpg","wordcount":"527","commentable":"false","byline":"Ashley Cowburn","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-12-